                text = "*(She looks at her scrolls, then at her own age-spotted hands, and a grave, grateful understanding settles over her.)* Outlive us both. *(quietly.)* ...You're *right*, and it's the *one* thing my *pride* never *let* me *do.* *(she touches the grammar.)* I *kept* the tongue *alive* — *in* *me.* In *one* *mind.* The *lonely* room, the *last* reader, the *keeper.* *(her voice tightens.)* And I told myself that was *devotion.* But it was *also* — *(she meets your eyes)* — it was *also* the *same* *crime* the *Wall* *commits.* A *tongue* in *one* *mind* is a *tongue* *one* *death* from *dead* *again.* I have been *guarding* the *literacy* the *Realms* needs the way a *miser* guards *coin* — *hoarded*, *singular*, *mortal.* *(she takes up a fresh sheet.)* So — *write* it *down.* A *primer.* The *whole* *grammar*, the *vocabulary*, the *strokes* and what they *mean* — *plain* enough that a *child*, a *mourner*, *anyone* with the *will* could *teach* *themselves* to *read* the *Wall*, with *no* *living* *teacher* *needed.* *(fierce.)* *Copy* it *wide.* Every *trustworthy* *scribe* — *Pol's* whole *leaking* *trade* turned to *this.* Until the *dead* *tongue* is not *kept* *alive* by *one* *old* *woman* but *written* *down*, *spread*, *unhoardable*, *immortal.* *(she meets your eyes, and there is peace in it.)* When *I* *die* — and I'm *old*, Returned, it *won't* be *long* — the *tongue* *must* *not* *die* *with* me, the way it *almost* did *before* I *taught* *you.* *(she begins to write.)* A *primer* the *Wall* can *never* *burn* out of *enough* *hands.* *That's* the *true* *end* of *forgetting-by-illiteracy*: not *one* reader, not *even* *two* — a *tongue* *written* *down* so *plainly* that *anyone* who *wants* to *read* their *dead* *can* *learn* *to.* *Help* me *write* the *primer.* Let the *literacy* *outlive* the *literate.*",
