                text = "*(Mistress Ekko stands before the Wall of the Faithless — the keeper of a dead tongue who learned, at sixty, that she'd kept the one key to the Wall's deepest lie — and whether you claimed your own unfinished name off the stone, read the dead their names so they'd learn they were known, taught the tongue to the Realms so the forgetting could never be re-enforced, carried the literacy to the Court, or wrote the primer that outlives every living reader, you carry away the sharpest of all the road's truths about the Wall: that it never made the Faithless nameless — it named them with terrible care, and then carved the names in a tongue it made certain no mourner could read, so that grief could stand before a wall of the named and believe it a wall of the nameless. The forgetting was never erasure. It was illiteracy, engineered and maintained for ten thousand years. And the unmaking of it is not a sword or a crown, but the most patient weapon there is: teaching the world to read its own dead.)*",
